  </figure>

  <p>
    This works, and it works well within its reach. But the descriptors are chosen, not learned. A
    person decides which target distances and angles to score, and the network only sees the world
    through that chosen list. Choose a list that misses a feature the chemistry cares about, and no
    amount of training recovers it. The next idea takes the choosing away from the person.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 2</span>The better answer: let the network learn its features</h2>

  <p>
    Stop fixing the features by hand. Give every atom a vector of numbers — call it the atom's
    <strong>feature vector</strong>, its private scratchpad — and let the network fill that scratchpad
    itself. At the start the scratchpad holds almost nothing: just the atom's element. The trick is
    how the scratchpads get filled in.
  </p>

  <p>
    They get filled by talking to neighbors. The process runs in <strong>rounds</strong>. In one
    round, every atom looks along each of its graph edges, takes a copy of that neighbor's
    scratchpad, and shapes it according to the edge between them — how far the neighbor is, in which
    direction. Each shaped copy is a <strong>message</strong>. The atom collects the messages from
    all its neighbors and adds them together — a sum, so the order of the neighbors never matters,
    the same permutation safety as before — and uses the total to update its own scratchpad. Every
    atom does this at once. This is <strong>message passing</strong>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Do it again. And again. After a few rounds, read ε<sub>i</sub> off each atom's final scratchpad
    with a small network, exactly as before, and sum to the energy. Nothing about the input changed;
    what changed is that the features fed to the readout were grown by the network instead of
    written down by a person.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 240" role="img" aria-label="One round of message passing on a four-atom graph: the center atom receives a shaped message along each edge from its neighbors, sums them, and updates its feature vector.">
