  </figure>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 3</span>What the messages carry</h2>

  <p>
    Message passing learns its own features, but it inherits a question from Chapter 2: how much of
    the geometry do the messages keep? The plainest version sends only scalars — numbers built from
    distances, like "this neighbor is 2.1 Å away." Scalars are invariant; they do not change when
    you turn the molecule, which is exactly what an energy needs. An early and influential model,
    <strong>SchNet</strong>, was built this way, on distances alone.
  </p>

  <p>
    Distance-only messages have the same blind spot the hand-built descriptors had before angles
    were added. Two arrangements can share every pairwise distance and still differ in shape. Take a
    triangle of three neighbors and squash it flat; the three edge lengths can be kept the same while
    the figure changes from open to nearly collinear. A model that hears only distances cannot tell
    the two apart, yet their energies differ.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 230" role="img" aria-label="Two three-atom arrangements with the same three pairwise distances but different shapes: one open triangle, one squashed nearly flat.">
        <text x="190" y="36" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">arrangement A</text>
        <g stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.6">
          <line x1="120" y1="160" x2="260" y2="160" />
          <line x1="120" y1="160" x2="190" y2="84" />
          <line x1="260" y1="160" x2="190" y2="84" />
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--ink)"><circle cx="120" cy="160" r="7"/><circle cx="260" cy="160" r="7"/><circle cx="190" cy="84" r="7"/></g>
        <text x="183" y="180" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">d₁</text>
        <text x="138" y="118" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">d₂</text>
        <text x="240" y="118" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">d₃</text>

        <text x="530" y="36" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">arrangement B</text>
        <g stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.6">
          <line x1="452" y1="150" x2="612" y2="150" />
          <line x1="452" y1="150" x2="500" y2="128" />
          <line x1="612" y1="150" x2="500" y2="128" />
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--ink)"><circle cx="452" cy="150" r="7"/><circle cx="612" cy="150" r="7"/><circle cx="500" cy="128" r="7"/></g>
        <text x="430" y="206" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small" style="fill:var(--oxblood);">same d₁, d₂, d₃</text>
        <text x="560" y="206" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small" style="fill:var(--oxblood);">— different shape</text>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 4</span>Two arrangements built from the same three pairwise distances <em>d</em><sub>1</sub>, <em>d</em><sub>2</sub>, <em>d</em><sub>3</sub>. One is open, one is squashed nearly flat. A model whose messages carry only distances reads them as identical; their true energies are not.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    There are two ways to fix this. The first is to put the missing geometry back in by hand: feed
    angles to the messages, the way the hand-built descriptors did. Models in the
    <strong>DimeNet</strong> and <strong>GemNet</strong> line do this, sending messages that carry
    angle information as well as distance. The features are still scalars — still invariant — but now
    they encode shape, not just spacing.
  </p>

  <p>
    The second way is deeper. Let the scratchpads themselves hold directional things. Instead of
    attaching a plain number to each neighbor, attach a little arrow that points along the bond. An
    arrow records direction, not just spacing. Beyond arrows there are more exotic relatives that
    encode how a quantity varies over directions at finer and finer resolution — an arrow is the
    coarsest of them. These directional building blocks are called <strong>spherical harmonics</strong>,
    and they are already the language physics uses to describe atomic orbitals and angular momentum.
    Their defining property is the one we need: when the molecule turns, they turn rigidly with it —
    they are <strong>equivariant</strong>, the same word Chapter 2 used for forces. Rotation now lives
    <em>inside</em> the network's hidden layers, not only at its input and output. Models in the
    <strong>NequIP</strong>, <strong>MACE</strong>, and <strong>Allegro</strong> family work this way.
  </p>

  <aside class="sidenote">
    <span class="sn-label">A point not to overclaim</span>
    Equivariant hidden features are not required for correct forces. Chapter 2 already showed that an
    invariant energy, differentiated, gives equivariant forces for free — and SchNet and DimeNet,
    whose insides are entirely invariant, get their forces exactly this way. The payoff of carrying
    equivariant features inside is not correctness but <em>efficiency</em>: a network that already
    speaks the language of rotation does not have to learn it from examples, and so learns the rest
    from far fewer of them. NequIP reported matching the accuracy of earlier invariant models with a
    small fraction of the training data they needed — on some benchmarks a tenth or a hundredth as
    many examples.
  </aside>

  <p>
    Whether the directional features are written in everyday <em>x, y, z</em> components or in the
    spherical-harmonic basis is a choice of bookkeeping, not a different species of model — the same
    rotating objects, two ways of writing them down. Depth is also not the only knob. In the
    message passing described so far, each message comes from one neighbor at a time, and the center
    atom mixes them by adding. A higher-body-order message is formed before it is sent: a neighbor
    combines its own feature with the features of the other atoms it shares with the center, so the
    center receives a single message that already encodes a three-atom relationship — center,
    neighbor, and neighbor's neighbor — in one round rather than two. <strong>Body order</strong> is
    the name for how many atoms a single message folds together this way: a plain message reaches
    two-atom order, a higher-body-order message reaches three- or four-atom order. Body order and
    depth are independent. MACE pushes body order high within each round, and for that reason needs
    only about two rounds where plainer models use five or six.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 4</span>A small map</h2>

  <p>
    Two questions sort most of these models. Do the hidden features stay invariant scalars, or do
    they carry equivariant direction? And does the network reach its accuracy through many shallow
    rounds, or through fewer rounds that each blend many atoms at once? Lay those two questions on a
    grid and the families fall into place.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
