        </defs>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 5</span>A rough map of the families. Left to right: hidden features that stay invariant versus features that carry equivariant direction. Bottom to top: many plain rounds versus fewer rounds that each mix many atoms. The map is a sketch, not a ranking.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Whichever corner a model sits in, one thing holds across nearly all of them. The network is built
    to produce the energy, a single invariant number, and the forces are taken by differentiating
    that energy — <em>F</em> = −∇<em>E</em>, the rule from Chapter 1. The forces are never a second,
    separate output that might quietly disagree with the energy; they are its exact slope, which is
    what keeps a long simulation from leaking or inventing energy as it runs.
  </p>

  <p>
    What we have now is a function with knobs: how many rounds, how high the body order, scalar
    features or equivariant ones. A function with knobs is useless until the knobs are set. Setting
    them means showing the network examples — and the examples have to come from somewhere. Where the
    numbers come from, and how the fit is actually made, is the next chapter.
  </p>
</Primer>
